	<item>
		<title>Comment on Chirp, Squawk, Cackle, or Honk* by Tomaž</title>
		<link>http://markos.gaivo.net/blog/?p=1203&#038;cpage=1#comment-325193</link>
		<dc:creator>Tomaž</dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 13 Jul 2014 11:08:25 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://markos.gaivo.net/blog/?p=1203#comment-325193</guid>
		<description>Hi Markos,

I certainly agree with what you say about Twitter encouraging instant gratification and short attention spans. But unfortunately that seems to be the general direction most of the popular communication on the web is heading for. These days almost everyone worries about getting imaginary internet points as well, whether they are likes, shares, upvotes or retweets. I don&#039;t see Twitter as special in this regard.

I&#039;ve recently reported a bug to GitHub. Their form encourages you to condense your report to 140 characters. My first reaction was to dismiss it as an unnecessary way to mimic Twitter, but now I think it&#039;s a valid way to make people think about brevity and skip the unnecessary fluff. Like it or not, there is so much communication going on these days that being able to compress your message to essentials is a valuable skill.

I don&#039;t think that Twitter can (or should) replace longer texts, but I think it serves a purpose. Similar to how SMS still lives in parallel to e-mail. Even historically, there was a place for very short texts like haikus and aphorisms.

A lot of what you are talking about here is specific to Twitter as a company, centralized service and their user interface. In our original discussion I was thinking more about the form of communication itself. Regarding that, I couldn&#039;t agree more with you. I would be much happier if Twitter would be replaced with StatusNet or some other de-centralized technology.</description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Hi Markos,</p>
<p>I certainly agree with what you say about Twitter encouraging instant gratification and short attention spans. But unfortunately that seems to be the general direction most of the popular communication on the web is heading for. These days almost everyone worries about getting imaginary internet points as well, whether they are likes, shares, upvotes or retweets. I don&#8217;t see Twitter as special in this regard.</p>
<p>I&#8217;ve recently reported a bug to GitHub. Their form encourages you to condense your report to 140 characters. My first reaction was to dismiss it as an unnecessary way to mimic Twitter, but now I think it&#8217;s a valid way to make people think about brevity and skip the unnecessary fluff. Like it or not, there is so much communication going on these days that being able to compress your message to essentials is a valuable skill.</p>
<p>I don&#8217;t think that Twitter can (or should) replace longer texts, but I think it serves a purpose. Similar to how SMS still lives in parallel to e-mail. Even historically, there was a place for very short texts like haikus and aphorisms.</p>
<p>A lot of what you are talking about here is specific to Twitter as a company, centralized service and their user interface. In our original discussion I was thinking more about the form of communication itself. Regarding that, I couldn&#8217;t agree more with you. I would be much happier if Twitter would be replaced with StatusNet or some other de-centralized technology.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
